regicide and terror, while articulating a compassionate, humanitarian vision, which became the moral basis for the modern French nation. Their credo of fraternity and unity, however, strangely depoliticized this supremely political act of regicide. Using theoretical insights from Tocqueville, Arendt, Rawls, Walzer, and others, Dunn explores the transformation of violent regicidal politics into an apolitical cult of ethical purity and an antidemocratic nationalist religion. Her book focuses on the fluidity of political myths. The figure of Louis XVI was transmuted into a Joan of Arc and a deified nation, and the notion of his sacrifice contributed to the disquieting myth of a mystical community of self- sacrificing citizens.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aHistorianszFrancexPolitical and social views. 0aKings and rulers in literature. 0aMonarchyzFrancexPublic opinion. 0aPublic opinionzFrancexHistoryy19th century. 0aRegicidexPublic opinion. 0aRegicidesxPublic opinion. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh  aAmerican Civil War.  aAmerican Revolution.  aAmerican amnesty.  aBelgians.  aBlanc, Louis.  aBourbon dynasty.  aBuchez, Philippe.  aCharles VII.  aDreyfus affair.  aEnglish readers.  aEnlightenment.  aFranco-Prussian War.  aGerman fascism.  aGerman war criminals.  aGrenoble conspiracy.  aHebrew Bible.  aIndian mythology.  aJesus Christ.  aJudaism.  aKoestler, Arthur.  aLakanal, Joseph.  aMarie-Antoinette.  aNapoleon I.  aNazism.  aOld Testament.  aabdication.  acapitalism.  achosen people concept.  acitizenship.  acivic virtue.  acivil disobedience.  acollaborationists.  acollective emotion.  ademocracy.  adivision of labor.  aemancipation of slaves.  aexecutioners.  aexpediency.  aextremist ideologies.  afascism.  af